estantism throughout the sixteenth century. By 1589, the friars used these same strategies on behalf of the Catholic League to try to prevent the succession of the Protestant heir presumptive, Henryof Navarre, to the French throne. This book contributes to our understanding of religion as a formative political impulse throughout the sixteenth century by linking the long-term political activism of the friars to the emergence of the French monarchy of the seventeenth century. Megan C. Armstrong is Associate Professor of History at McMaster University.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 28. Mrz 2024) 0aReligion and politicsxFrancexHistory, 16th century. 0aReligion and politicszFrancexHistoryy16th century. 4aEarly Modern History. 4aFrench Studies. 4aHistory of Religion. 4aModern History. 7aRELIGION / History.2bisacsh  aFranciscan order.  aFrench monarchy.  aMegan C. Armstrong.  aWars of Religion.  apolitical activism.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertBoydell and Brewer Complete eBook-Package pre 2013z978311143139040uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/9781580466301?locatt=mode:legacy40uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781580466301423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9781580466301/original  a978-3-11-143139-0  Boydell and Brewer Complete eBook-Package pre 2013b2013  aGBV-deGruyter-alles